s clinically focused on the details of the language. Furthermore, it dedicates a large section to a European missionary who documented some of the language into French. %0a%3c %0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miami-Illinois_language %0a%3c http://www.native-languages.org/miami-illinois.htm %0a%3c https://www.miamioh.edu/myaamia-center/index.html %0a%3c https://miamination.com/node/11 %0a---%0a> I chose Skokie, Illinois because that is where I grew up. The midwest has a long history with indigenous appropriation. Skokie’s village insignia is still problematically a Native American chief. One of the tribes who were the traditional stewards of the land was the Myaamia ([maɪʝmiə]) tribe. They are often referred to as the Miami tribe but the true name in their language is Myaamia, meaning “the downstream people”. I don’t think this tribe is officially listed in the cession, but cession 148 is a treaty that extended over land that is considered part of the tribe’s homeland before forced removal from various regions concentrated the tribe in Miami, Oklahoma. The spoken language is the Miami-Illinois language. The tribe is working hard and several programs and  initiatives related to language learning. There is also a Myaamia Center at Miami University which has a language research office dedicated to studying and collecting knowledge on the language. The office is undertaking many projects, including an online learner’s dictionary and teaching grammar of the language and contributing academic publications about the language in the linguistics field. I was unable to find information on who and how many folks speak the language, but it seems like it is in use currently, and is used day to day. For example, many words are incorporated in the history section of the Myaamia tribe’s official website. %0a> %0a> In reading the Wikipedia page for this language it is clear my summary definitely would have been different than the one I have already written. It seems factual enough, but the real differences are in emphasis. The focus and purpose of the Myaamia produced materials are about their history and the way their people were forcibly removed and killed in large numbers and that currently they are doing their best to revive their language and preserve their community and culture. Wikipedia glosses over these facts and is clinically focused on the details of the language. Furthermore, it dedicates a large section to a European missionary who documented some of the language into French. %0a> %0a> https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miami-Illinois_language %0a> http://www.native-languages.org/miami-illinois.htm %0a> https://www.miamioh.edu/myaamia-center/index.html %0a> https://miamination.com/node/11 %0a59,66c59,66%0a%3c I thought it was interesting to see that the original article found a lot of the differences that Dr. Leonard might predict based on the article of his that we read in class. In particular, I wanted to examine why Wikipedia might include different information than the Myaamia themselves would advertise about their language.%0a%3c %0a%3c Wikipedia, an outside source, might see Myaamia as more of a historical artefact than a living language. Because there were, at one point, no remaining living speakers of myaamia, the contributors to Wikipedia treat it like a dead language. As such, they focus on how it has been documented and understood by European scholars as opposed to its relationship to the culture of the people today.%0a%3c %0a%3c On the other hand, the Miami tribe website emphasizes the sorts of programs that Leonard discusses. In particular, it pushes back against the narrative that myaamia is a dead language and understands it as something of the present.%0a%3c %0a%3c As such, we can only hope that efforts like those of the Miami tribe are successful, not only for the sake of preserving their language, but also in challenging dominant discourses about the way in which indigenous people and their culture are only relics of a time gone by.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> I thought it was interesting to see that the original article found a lot of the differences that Dr. Leonard might predict based on the article of his that we read in class. In particular, I wanted to examine why Wikipedia might include different information than the Myaamia themselves would advertise about their language.%0a> %0a> Wikipedia, an outside source, might see Myaamia as more of a historical artefact than a living language. Because there were, at one point, no remaining living speakers of myaamia, the contributors to Wikipedia treat it like a dead language. As such, they focus on how it has been documented and understood by European scholars as opposed to its relationship to the culture of the people today.%0a> %0a> On the other hand, the Miami tribe website emphasizes the sorts of programs that Leonard discusses. In particular, it pushes back against the narrative that myaamia is a dead language and understands it as something of the present.%0a> %0a> As such, we can only hope that efforts like those of the Miami tribe are successful, not only for the sake of preserving their language, but also in challenging dominant discourses about the way in which indigenous people and their culture are only relics of a time gone by.%0a> %0a75c75%0a%3c (:if exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author}:)%0a---%0a> (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a
